===Etymology 1===
{{PIE root|en|kʷ}}
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|how}}, {{m|enm|hou}}, {{m|enm|hu}}, {{m|enm|hwu}}, {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|hū}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*hwō}}, from the same root as {{m|ang|hwæt||who, what}}. /hw/ > /h/ due to [[w:Wh-cluster reductions|''wh''-cluster reduction]] in {{etyl|ang|-}}; compare {{m|en|who}}, which underwent this change later, and thus is spelt ''wh'' ({{etyl|enm|-}} spelling of /hw/) but pronounced /h/ (it previously had a different vowel, hence avoided the spelling and sound change in Old English). Vowel change per [[Great Vowel Shift]].

Akin to Scots {{m|sco|hoo}}, {{m|sco|foo||how}}, Saterland Frisian {{m|stq|wo||how}}, West Frisian {{m|fy|hoe||how}}, {{cog|nds|ho}}, {{m|nds|wo}}, {{m|nds|wu||how}}, {{cog|nl|hoe||how}}, {{cog|de|wie||how}}, Swedish {{m|sv|hur||how}}. See {{m|en|who}} and compare {{m|en|why}}.

